recordings.rmk:
Blue Tits are unusual because one of the species' alarm notes is, to my ears, identical to the same phrase used by male Blue Tits as song. A longer discussion of this topic can be read at XC218741. The present recording features a Blue Tit (sex unknown) that was, for want of a better word, haranguing me as I walked along a road early in the morning. Blue Tits are very assertive and such 'bossy boots' behaviour is quite normal. I consider that Blue Tit, even more so than Great Tit (and certainly more than Coal Tit) is a self-styled look-out and will approach the source of any form of disturbance that alters the status quo of the Blue Tit neighbourhood.

Background: singing Blackbirds

I find Blue Tit vocabulary puzzling.  Nevertheless, it is stimulating to realise that there is so much to learn about 'common or garden' birds. The sweet aria employed by males as song is also used in situations ranging from irritation at the bird's personal space being invaded (such as when walking into a garden that is regarded by a Blue Tit as its fiefdom) or when there is a situation of genuine alarm, perhaps a passing Sparrowhawk or stalking cat. I have yet to scrutinise individual Blue Tits that produce the sound in 'non-song' situations to check their sex. I know that telling the sex of a Blue Tit is often not straightforward but it would be interesting to know if either sex produces 'song alarm' in circumstances that are purely alarm related. In other words, as well as males using the composition for song, do females utter the same sound when they feel piqued or wish to raise alarm?[ An example of a Blue Tit, of unknown sex, issuing alarm calls resembling male song can be heard at XC218749.]

This recording appears to feature a male broadcasting song for no other reason than courtship. I was indoors when I heard the sound so my presence had no influence. By way of describing the sound, the initial three notes resemble three (similar) peaks and span just under 0.5 seconds. The subsequent part of the phrase is a tremolo. Most times when I hear the full phrase I reckon that the tremolo is of longer duration than the opening notes (sometimes there are two, rather than three opening notes, as in XC218749). When you look at the Xeno-canto sonogram it is clear that the tremolo has, at the very beginning, slightly higher pitched notes. Following these, the majority of the tremolo comprises homogeneous notes. However, my ear cannot distinguish any difference (even a subtle difference) across the full span of the tremolo. To me, the Blue Tit's phrase is two-parted: first, the sharp 'peaked' notes; second, the 'trembling' tremolo. 

Luckily bird voices do not change. A good analogy will, therefore, remain a good analogy, no matter how long ago it was patented. My favourite piece of writing that encapsulates Blue Tit's song is from The Handbook of British Birds (1940) by Witherby et al. In it, a line credited to H G Alexander states, 'Song: a rapid, liquid trill introduced by two or three single notes, "tsee-tsee-tsu-tsuhuhuhuhuhu," almost like a musical escape of water.'

recordings.file-name: XC211280-Blue Tit post hawk. Garden. 20 Jan 15 1117hrs.mp3
recordings.rmk: This recording captures the aftermath of a Sparrowhawk passing through a suburban garden. Although all small songbirds in the vicinity panicked, none were caught. As normal practice, even when the attack has passed, Blue Tits utter a sweet-sounding 'hovering trill' that serves as a warning indicating that a Sparrowhawk is in the area and may return. The same sound - that is deceptively angelic and therefore a counter-intuitive vocalisation, given its function - is used in other situations where a Blue Tit is anxious or in a self-appointed vigilante mood. For example, a person walking through territory (or even walking from indoors and into a garden to fill a feeder) will elicit the sound. The trill can be heard several times on the recording, and even from both in a pair just after 0:01. Other examples of the call are at 0:10, just after 0:13 and at 0:16. A different 'annoyed' call that is a common component of much Blue Tit vocabulary is a very fast stuttering 'tit/tit/tit'. It can be heard just after 0:29.  A standard Blackbird 'freaking out' exclamation occurs just before 0:06.  House Sparrows resort to a double-tap when they are stressed and examples are intermingled in the background, such as 0:11, 0:13 and 0:15.
